content.description: This route follows a direct line, straight up, a few feet left of the bolted "Corner Route". A little thin on the lower section but pretty easy from just above the second bolt on up.

This route follows the steeper rock just right of the obvious, fourth class ledges. It is right on the corner. It is usually done as a solo and it scared me because of the jagged landing should you peel off. But, I am kind of a wuss.

Start to the right of Chimney Crack. Climb directly up to the anchor of Step Aside on sloping edges. This route is fun and challenging. The crux is down low on the climb but the crimping is sustained over its short length. I've heard the crimps down low described as trying to grab "rounded ice cubes." One of the best at Rocklands and certainly the most physically challenging.
content.protection: Toprope only. It would make a fun lead if it were bolted.
content.location: First climb to the right of Chimney Crack at the Rocklands area of Cerro Cabrillo.

content.description: Follow the easy, right-leaning crack just right of the cleft (the beginning of Kermit Crack). About 15-18 feet up, begin angling left at a 45 degree angle towards a bulge. the bulge is smoother and more overhanging than you think. Go over the bulge and you are at the anchors.
Follow the dark streak left of the bolted corner route.
Start a few feet left of the two "dishes" on the right side of the formation. Goes straight up to a depression, then curves slightly right for the remainder.

This route starts up the left side a few feet beneath an old, rusty spinner. You go straight up for a few feet on crimps and then angle slightly right to a fun undercling. the flake kind of flexes if you really pull on it(but, then again, I am not very small). Above the undercling, continue traversing to the right to end at the anchors.
If Kermit Crack is a good intro to cracks for new climbers, Kermit Face is a good intro to face climbing for new climbers.
content.protection: 3 bolts, new 2 bolt anchor with rap rings
content.location: The bolted face between Kermit's Crack and West (Easy) Corner.

content.description: From Hwy 1 follow South Bay Blvd. to the first parking lot on the left side. Follow the trail up to the quarry (visible from the parking lot). See picture for more detail on finding the route.
content.protection: Follow the obvious crack about 15 feet to the right of Chimney Crack. Top rope or pro small to 2.5". Good first trad lead.

content.description: Start just beneath the two "dishes" on the right side of the rock.Climb at an angle to the right across the smooth, light-colored rock. When you reach the more featured dark rock, there is a short traverse to the left and then staright up.

This route follows the corner to the left of the deep cleft in the rock. The three bolts are obvious. There was some discussion on this forum about it being stiffer than 5.4. the estimates ranged from 5.4-5.7. This is a perfect climb to have someone do their first lead on.
content.protection: Three solid bolts make this a fun lead for beginners.

content.description: This is the overhanging section just to the left of the cleft. The holds are not very visible from below, and when you do find them they are small and sharp. the line goes straight up, passing the right edge of a small arch about 2/3 of the way up. This route seemed a lot harder than 5.9.
A fun, part crack, part stemming climb. Go up to the back of the cleft in the rock and climb staright up.
